      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'Should I take vitamin D3 with K2?',
      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Combining vitamin D3 with vitamin K2 is increasingly recommended by nutrition researchers because the two vitamins work synergistically in calcium metabolism. Vitamin D3 increases calcium absorption from the intestine, while vitamin K2 activates osteocalcin and matrix GLA protein — the proteins that direct calcium into bones and teeth and away from soft tissues like arteries and kidneys. Without adequate K2, the increased calcium absorption from D3 supplementation could theoretically contribute to arterial calcification rather than bone mineralization. A 2017 study in the International Journal of Endocrinology found that combined D3+K2 supplementation improved bone mineral density more effectively than D3 alone. If your vitamin D gummy does not include K2, consider a separate K2 supplement (100-200mcg MK-7 form) taken with the same meal.' },
    },
  ],
};
