    <!-- VITAMIN D DOSING GUIDE -->
    <div class="ing-box">
      <h4>Vitamin D Dosing Guide: How Much D3 Do You Actually Need?</h4>
      <p>Vitamin D requirements depend on your current 25(OH)D blood level, age, skin color, latitude, sun exposure, and body composition. A blood test is the only way to determine your optimal dose, but these guidelines provide a starting framework.</p>

      <div class="vs-strip">
        <div class="vs-item">
          <strong>600-800 IU — Official RDA</strong>
          <p>The Institute of Medicine's RDA (600 IU for ages 19-70, 800 IU for 70+) targets bone health only and is considered insufficient by many endocrinologists. This dose maintains 25(OH)D around 20 ng/mL — the minimum to prevent rickets and osteomalacia, not the optimal range for immune function and disease prevention.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="vs-item">
          <strong>1,000-2,000 IU — Daily Maintenance</strong>
          <p>The Endocrine Society recommends 1500-2000 IU daily for adults to maintain serum 25(OH)D between 30-50 ng/mL. This range is associated with reduced respiratory infection risk, improved bone density, and better mood regulation. The most appropriate dose for the general population taking vitamin D for prevention.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="vs-item">
          <strong>4,000-5,000 IU — Deficiency Repletion</strong>
          <p>Used to correct documented vitamin D deficiency (25(OH)D below 20 ng/mL) over 8-12 weeks. At this dose, 25(OH)D rises approximately 20-25 ng/mL, bringing most deficient individuals into the sufficient range. Should be followed by a retest and step-down to maintenance dosing once levels normalize.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="vs-item">
          <strong>10,000+ IU — Physician-Supervised Only</strong>
          <p>Megadoses above 10,000 IU daily are occasionally used for severe deficiency or malabsorption conditions (celiac, Crohn's, gastric bypass). This dose carries real risk of hypervitaminosis D and hypercalcemia. Never use without direct physician supervision and regular blood monitoring of both 25(OH)D and serum calcium.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="warn-box">
        <div class="warn-box-ico"><Icon name="warning" size={18} /></div>
        <p><strong>Vitamin D toxicity is slow but dangerous:</strong> Because vitamin D is fat-soluble and stored in adipose tissue, toxicity develops gradually over weeks to months of excessive intake (typically >10,000 IU/day). Symptoms include nausea, vomiting, weakness, kidney stones, and hypercalcemia that can cause cardiac arrhythmias. The 4000 IU Tolerable Upper Intake Level is conservative but provides a meaningful safety buffer. If taking 5000 IU daily, monitor 25(OH)D levels every 3-6 months.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

