    <!-- FAQ SECTION -->
    <h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions About Vitamin D Gummies</h2>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>How much vitamin D should I take daily?</summary>
      <p>The RDA is 600 IU for adults aged 19-70 and 800 IU for 70+. However, the Endocrine Society and many researchers recommend 1000-2000 IU daily for most adults to maintain optimal serum 25(OH)D between 40-60 ng/mL. Individuals with documented deficiency may need 4000-5000 IU under physician supervision for 8-12 weeks. The Tolerable Upper Intake Level is 4000 IU per day. A 25(OH)D blood test is the only way to determine your ideal dose.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>What is the difference between vitamin D2 and vitamin D3?</summary>
      <p>Vitamin D2 (ergocalciferol) comes from fungi; D3 (cholecalciferol) is the form your skin produces from sunlight. A 2012 meta-analysis found D3 is 87% more potent than D2 at raising serum levels and produces 2-3 times greater body storage. D3 also has a longer half-life for stable blood levels. All 8 gummies in our guide use the superior D3 form.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Can vitamin D gummies cause side effects?</summary>
      <p>At standard doses (1000-2000 IU daily), side effects are extremely rare. Chronic intake above 10,000 IU daily can cause vitamin D toxicity (hypervitaminosis D), leading to hypercalcemia with nausea, weakness, kidney stones, and potentially kidney failure. At gummy doses (1000-5000 IU), toxicity is essentially unreported. The key risk is combining multiple D-containing supplements without tracking total daily intake.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Should I take vitamin D with food or on an empty stomach?</summary>
      <p>Vitamin D is fat-soluble and absorbs best with dietary fat. A 2015 study found taking D with the largest meal increased absorption by approximately 50%. Gummies provide a small advantage because they inherently contain some fat. For maximum absorption, take vitamin D gummies with a meal containing healthy fats like avocado, nuts, olive oil, or eggs.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>How do I know if I am vitamin D deficient?</summary>
      <p>The only reliable method is a 25(OH)D blood test. Below 20 ng/mL is deficient, 20-29 is insufficient, 30+ is sufficient. Symptoms include fatigue, bone pain, muscle weakness, frequent infections, slow wound healing, and depression. Risk factors: living above the 37th parallel, dark skin, obesity, limited sun exposure, age 65+, and malabsorption conditions. An estimated 42% of American adults are deficient.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Can I get enough vitamin D from sunlight alone?</summary>
      <p>Theoretically yes, practically no for most Americans. Your skin produces 10,000-20,000 IU from 15-30 minutes of midday UVB exposure. However, UVB sufficient for D synthesis only reaches the US from April-October at midday. Winter at latitudes above 37°N produces zero vitamin D regardless of exposure. Sunscreen SPF 15 blocks 93% of UVB, dark skin needs 3-6x more exposure, and aging reduces production by 75%. Supplementation is necessary for most Americans at least 6 months per year.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Does vitamin D help with depression and mood?</summary>
      <p>Growing evidence supports this connection. Vitamin D receptors exist throughout mood-regulating brain regions. A 2014 meta-analysis of 31,424 participants found low D levels significantly associated with increased depression risk. A 2020 umbrella review confirmed statistically significant positive effects on depression, especially in deficient individuals. Seasonal Affective Disorder closely mirrors seasonal D deficiency patterns.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Should I take vitamin D3 with K2?</summary>
      <p>Combining D3 with K2 is increasingly recommended. D3 increases calcium absorption, while K2 activates proteins (osteocalcin, matrix GLA protein) that direct calcium into bones rather than arteries. A 2017 study found combined D3+K2 improved bone density more than D3 alone. If your D3 gummy lacks K2, consider a separate K2 supplement (100-200mcg MK-7 form) taken with the same meal.</p>
    </details>

